Linux systems generate huge text data (logs, configs, CSVs).These three commands help us search, analyze, and modify text efficiently.
1ï¸âƒ£ grep--> grep is a command-line tool used to search for a specific pattern or word inside text files or command output.
Why do we need grep?
  To find errors in logs
  To filter command output
  To locate configuration entries
  Saves time instead of manual searching

Syntax
grep "pattern" filename   (will show the line containing the word pattern)

ğŸ”¹ Useful Options
| Option | Purpose            |
| ------ | ------------------ |
| `-i`   | Ignore case        |
| `-n`   | Show line number   |
| `-r`   | Search recursively |     ğŸ‘‰ Ek directory ke andar jitni bhi files & sub-directories hain, un sab me search karna.
| `-v`   | Exclude pattern    |     ğŸ‘‰ Jo pattern diya hai usko chhod ke baaki sab dikhao

2ï¸âƒ£awk --> awk is a powerful text-processing tool used to work with columns (fields) and records in a file.
          awk is used for column-based data extraction and processing.

Why do we need awk?
To extract specific columns
To analyze structured text (tables, CSVs)
To generate reports
To process command outputs

ğŸ”§ Syntax
awk '{action}' filename

ğŸ§ª Example
File: employees.txt
    John 5000 HR
    Alice 7000 IT
    Bob 4000 Finance

awk '{print $1}' employees.txt
0/p >John
    Alice
    Bob

awk '$2 > 5000 {print $1, $2}' employees.txt
o/p: Alice 7000

3ï¸âƒ£ sed --> sed (Stream Editor) is used to edit, replace, or delete text in a stream or file, usually without opening the file.
sed is used to modify text automatically.

â“Why do we need sed?
To automate text changes
To update config files
To perform find-and-replace
To modify files in scripts & pipelines

ğŸ”§ Syntax
sed 's/old/new/' filename      (only for preview data is changed)
sed -i 's/old/new/' filename    (permanent data change)
sed -i.bak 's/old/new/' filename  (Backup ke saath change)
File: config.env
APP_ENV=dev
PORT=8080

Command
sed 's/dev/prod/' config.env

Output
APP_ENV=prod
PORT=8080

grep â†’ find
awk  â†’ extract 
sed  â†’ modify
